SIMPLE: place
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Place
<hw>Place</hw> <pr>(pl⟦amac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>platea</ets> a street, an area, a courtyard, from Gr.
<grk>platei^a</grk> a street, properly fem. of <grk>platy`s</grk>, flat,
broad; akin to Skr. <ets>p⟦rsdot⟧thu</ets>, Lith. <ets>platus</ets>. Cf.
<er>Flawn</er>, <er>Piazza</er>, <er>Plate</er>, <er>Plaza</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Any portion of space regarded as measured off or
distinct from all other space, or appropriated to some definite object
or use; position; ground; site; spot; rarely, unbounded space.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here is the <qex>place</qex> appointed.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>place</qex> can be for us⟦br⟧
Within heaven's bound?</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The word <qex>place</qex> has sometimes a more confused sense, and
stands for that space which any body takes up; and so the universe is a
<qex>place</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A broad way in a city; an open space; an area; a
court or short part of a street open only at one end.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Hangman boys in the market <xex>place</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A position which is occupied and held; a dwelling; a
mansion; a village, town, or city; a fortified town or post; a
stronghold; a region or country.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Are you native of this <qex>place</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Rank; degree; grade; order of priority, advancement,
dignity, or importance; especially, social rank or position; condition;
also, official station; occupation; calling.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The enervating
magic of <xex>place</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hawthorne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men in great <qex>place</qex> are thrice servants.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I know my <qex>place</qex> as I would they should do theirs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Vacated or relinquished space; room; stead (the
departure or removal of another being or thing being implied).</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>place</xex> of Lord Bassanio.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A definite position or passage of a
document.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>place</qex> of the scripture which he read was this.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts viii. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Ordinal relation; position in the order of
proceeding; <as>as, he said in the first <ex>place</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Reception; effect; -- implying the making room
for.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My word hath no <qex>place</qex> in you.</q> <rj><qau>John viii.
37.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Position in the heavens, as of
a heavenly body; -- usually defined by its right ascension and
declination, or by its latitude and longitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Racing)</fld> <def>The position of first, second,
or third at the finish, esp. the second position. In betting, to win a
bet on a horse for <xex>place</xex> it must, in the United States,
finish first or second, in England, usually, first, second, or
third.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Place of arms</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a place
calculated for the rendezvous of men in arms, etc., as a fort which
affords a safe retreat for hospitals, magazines, etc.</cd>
<au>Wilhelm.</au> -- <col><b>High place</b></col> <fld>(Script.)</fld>,
<cd>a mount on which sacrifices were offered.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Him that
offereth in the <xex>high place</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Jer. xlviii. 35.</au>
-- <col><b>In place</b></col>, <cd>in proper position; timely.</cd> --
<col><b>Out of place</b></col>, <cd>inappropriate; ill-timed; <as>as,
his remarks were <ex>out of place</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Place
kick</b></col> <fld>(Football)</fld>, <cd>the act of kicking the ball
after it has been placed on the ground.</cd> -- <col><b>Place
name</b></col>, <cd>the name of a place or locality.</cd> <au>London
Academy.</au> -- <col><b>To give place</b></col>, <cd>to make room; to
yield; to give way; to give advantage.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Neither <xex>give
place</xex> to the devil.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Eph. iv. 27.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Let all
the rest <xex>give place</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To have
place</b></col>, <cd>to have a station, room, or seat; as, such desires
can <xex>have</xex> no <xex>place</xex> in a good heart.</cd> --
<col><b>To take place</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To come to pass; to
occur; as, the ceremony will not <xex>take place</xex>.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To take precedence or priority.</cd> <au>Addison.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To take effect; to prevail.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧If your
doctrine <xex>takes place</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Berkeley.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧But
none of these excuses would <xex>take place</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Spenser.</au> -- <col><b>To take the place of</b></col>, <cd>to be
substituted for.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Situation; seat; abode; position; locality;
location; site; spot; office; employment; charge; function; trust;
ground; room; stead.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Place</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Place
<hw>Place</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Placed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Placing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>placer</ets>. See <er>Place</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To assign a place to; to put in a particular spot or place, or in a
certain relative position; to direct to a particular place; to fix; to
settle; to locate; <as>as, to <ex>place</ex> a book on a shelf; to
<ex>place</ex> balls in tennis.</as></def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Put.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon my head they <qex>placed</qex> a fruitless crown.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put or set in a particular rank, office, or
position; to surround with particular circumstances or relations in
life; to appoint to certain station or condition of life; <as>as, in
whatever sphere one is <ex>placed</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Place</qex> such over them to be rulers.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xviii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put out at interest; to invest; to loan; <as>as,
to <ex>place</ex> money in a bank</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To set; to fix; to repose; <as>as, to <ex>place</ex>
confidence in a friend</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My resolution 's
<xex>placed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To attribute; to ascribe; to set down.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Place</qex> it for her chief virtue.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Racing)</fld> <def>To determine or announce the
place of at the finish. Usually, in horse racing only the first three
horses are <xex>placed</xex> officially.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Rugby Football)</fld> <def>To place-kick ( a
goal).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>to recognize or identify (a person).</def>
<mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Placebo</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
